<p>During his speech at the 2014 <a href="http://www.almaawards.com/">NCLR Alma Awards</a>, Guillermo del Toro shared a story of his friend and colleague, Guillermo Navarro (<em>Pacific Rim</em>) of their early days in the film industry. Simply put, a Hollywood studio executive told Navarro that he did not need a Mexican filmmaker, he already had a gardener.</p>

<p>â€œWhen I came here, to America, at the beginning of the â€™90s it was a very different panorama,â€ Del Toro explained to the star studded crowd of the Alma awards. Founded by the National Council of La Raza, the Alma awards have been honoring and celebrating for 15 years the fair and appropriate representation of Latinos in music, film and television. This year Del Toro was awarded the Anthony Quinn Award for Industry Excellence. â€œAnd we need to recognize that we have taken huge steps forward. Thereâ€™s much more to do, we are going to do it together,â€ Del Toro said.</p>

<p>_The BookÂ __of LifeÂ _is another huge step forward and one that targets the misrepresentation of Latinos at an early stage, youth. Â The American perception of Mexico â€” and by extension Latino America â€” is not exactly at a positive place. The <a href="http://www.huffingtonpost.com/aviva-chomsky/americas-continuing-border-crisis_b_5708085.html">border crisis</a> has revealed not only the ugly side of immigration policy but the ignorance, cruelty and racism attached to it. More than ever, being Latino is seen by some as a threat (however irrational) to so-called â€œAmerican valuesâ€ and the vast, diverse culture of Latino America is associated with the negative mess occurring at the border.</p>

